We are missing an important summary.

Correlation

Correlation

The correlation of a list of pairs \( (x_1, y_1), \dots , (x_n, y_n) \) is defined as

\[ \rho = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i-\mu_x}{\sigma_x} \right)\left( \frac{y_i-\mu_y}{\sigma_y} \right) \]

For father and son heights we have:

father.son %>% summarize(cor(fheight, sheight))

  cor(fheight, sheight)
1                   0.5

Correlation is between -1 and 1

To see this

\[ \rho = \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( \frac{x_i-\mu_x}{\sigma_x} \right)^2 \]

\[ = 1/\sigma^2 \frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n \left( x_i-\mu_x \right)^2 = 1 \]

Visualizing Correlation

Anscombe's quartet

Stratification

Connection to Correlation

Regression line

The points above define the regression line:

\[ \left( \frac{y_i-\mu_y}{\sigma_y} \right) = \rho \left( \frac{x_i-\mu_x}{\sigma_x} \right) \]

Note this is a line with \[ m = \rho \frac{\sigma_y}{\sigma_x} \]

\[ b=\mu_y - m \mu_x \]

Regression line

If we standardize the data then the line has slope \( \rho \) and 0 intercept:

Regression line

The regression line goes through the conditional averages

Bivariate Normal

n <- 250
cors <- c(-0.5,0,0.5,0.9)
dat <- lapply(cors,function(r) 
  MASS::mvrnorm(n,c(0,0), matrix(c(1,r,r,1),2,2)))

Bivariate Normal

\[ f_{Y \mid X=x} \mbox{ is the conditional distribution and } \mbox{E}(Y \mid X=x) \mbox{ is the conditional expected value.} \]

We can derive this: \[ \mbox{E}(Y | X=x) = \mu_Y + \rho \frac{X-\mu_X}{\sigma_X}\sigma_Y \] Note that this is a line with slope \( \rho \frac{\sigma_Y}{\sigma_X} \).

And therefore: \[ \frac{\mbox{E}(Y \mid X=x) - \mu_Y}{\sigma_Y} = \rho \frac{x-\mu_X}{\sigma_X} \]

Variance explained

The standard deviation of the conditional distribution described above is:

\[ \mbox{Var}(Y \mid X=x ) \sqrt{1-\rho^2} \sigma_y \]

Linear Models

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \varepsilon_i, i=1,\dots,N \]

Two regression Lines

Falling Object

Galileo's data motivates a linear model:

\[ Y_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x_i + \beta_2 x_i^2 + \varepsilon_i, i=1,\dots,n \]

Least Squares

\[ \sum_{i=1}^n \left\{ Y_i - \left(\beta_0 + \sum_{j=1}^p \beta_j x_{i,j}\right)\right\}^2 \]

The `lm` function

fit <- falling_object %>% mutate(time_sq = time^2) %>% lm(y~time+time_sq, data=.)

HR and Runs

Let's Use the data in the Team table to explore the relationship between HR and runs per game in 1999. Let's make a plot to see if perhaps HR predicts runs.

library(Lahman)
library(broom)
dat <- Teams %>%
  filter(yearID == 1999) %>%
  mutate(R = R / G, HR = HR / G)

Linear Model

\[ R_i = \beta_0 + \beta_1 HR_i + \varepsilon_i, \hat{\beta}_1=1.7 \]

Estimate is a Random Variable

Fit the model every year:

res <- Teams %>% filter(yearID >= 1961) %>%
  mutate(R = R / G, HR = HR / G) %>%
  group_by(yearID) %>%
  do(tidy(lm(R ~ HR, data = .))) %>%
  filter(term == "HR")
sd(res$estimate)

[1] 0.33

Estimate Properties

CLT for regression

fit <- dat  %>%
  lm(R ~ HR, data = .)
